title: Number Theory
text:
**Definition
Number

Definition

A number is a mathematical object primarily used for counting and/or measuring/quantifying some objects

Types of number

There are different types of numbers and they mostly exist as units within a hierarchy/subsets of some larger sets based on their properties, hence, they are also referred to as number sets/systems
Each type is sometimes denoted by a different symbol due to its significance


Some types of number in hierarchy


Complex (\(\mathbb{C}\))

Imaginary
Real (\(\mathbb{R}\))

Rational (\(\mathbb{Q}\))

Integer (\(\mathbb{Z}\))

Natural (\(\mathbb{N}\))
Negative integers

Fraction

Irrational

Algebraic irrational
Transcendental







Natural Numbers

Introduction

Natural numbers are a set of numbers that is considered to be the most basic/primitive type of numbers (i.e. being the lowest level in the number type hierarchy)
Aka “counting numbers”

Conceptual Definition

\(\mathbb{N} = 0, 1, 2, 3, ...\)

Notes

Historically, natural numbers have been defined as all positive integers (\(1, 2, 3, ...\)), which means that zero has been excluded as zero wasn’t conceptualized as a number. In more recent times, zero is generally considered as a number, hence, natural numbers are defined as all non-negative integers (\(0, 1, 2, 3, ...\)), hence, they are also known as that. People using the former definition includes Michael Spivak (Spivak, 2008) while those using the latter definition includes Terence Tao (Tao, 2016)
